zation,&#x201d; Cell 163 (2015): 123&#x2013;133.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC5149108</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">26406374</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Nedelsky N. B. and Taylor J. P., &#x201c;Pathological Phase Transitions in ALS&#x2010;FTD Impair Dynamic RNA&#x2010;Protein Granules,&#x201d; RNA 28 (2022): 97&#x2013;113.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC8675280</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">34706979</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Kim G., Gautier O., Tassoni&#x2010;Tsuchida E., Ma X. R., and Gitler A. D., &#x201c;ALS Genetics: Gains, Losses, and Implications for Future Therapies,&#x201d; Neuron 108 (2020): 822&#x2013;842.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC7736125</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">32931756</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Goutman S. A., Hardiman O., Al&#x2010;Chalabi A., et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;Emerging Insights Into the Complex Genetics and Pathophysiology of Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis,&#x201d; Lancet Neurology 21 (2022): 465&#x2013;479.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC9513754</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">35334234</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Lee B. P., Pilling L. C., Bandinelli S., Ferrucci L., Melzer D., and Harries L. W., &#x201c;The Transcript Expression Levels of HNRNPM, HNRNPA0 and AKAP17A Splicing Factors May Be Predictively Associated With Ageing Phenotypes in Human Peripheral Blood,&#x201d; Biogerontology 20 (2019): 649&#x2013;663.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC6733819</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">31292793</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status=\"MEDLINE\" Owner=\"NLM\" IndexingMethod=\"Automated\"><PMID Version=\"1\">41117127</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>21</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>23</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel=\"Print\"><Journal><ISSN IssnType=\"Electronic\">1468-1331</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium=\"Internet\"><Volume>32</Volume><Issue>10</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Oct</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>European journal of neurology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Eur J Neurol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Monoclonal Gammopathy in Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis: No Impact on Clinical Progression and Immunotherapy Outcomes.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>e70376</StartPage><MedlinePgn>e70376</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType=\"pii\" ValidYN=\"Y\">e70376</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType=\"doi\" ValidYN=\"Y\">10.1111/ene.70376</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label=\"BACKGROUND\" NlmCategory=\"BACKGROUND\">The association between amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) and monoclonal gammopathy has been proposed, but evidence on its prevalence, clinical relevance, and treatment response remains limited, especially in Asian populations. This study aimed to investigate the prevalence of monoclonal gammopathy in Korean patients with ALS and evaluate the impact of immunotherapy.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label=\"METHODS\" NlmCategory=\"METHODS\">This registry-based study analyzed Korean patients with ALS at a tertiary referral hospital (2005-2023). All patients underwent electrophoresis and immunofixation electrophoresis to detect monoclonal gammopathy. Clinical progression was assessed using ALSFRS-R scores, disease progression rate (&#x394;FS), survival analysis, and electrophysiological evaluations.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label=\"RESULTS\" NlmCategory=\"RESULTS\">Among 2400 patients with ALS, monoclonal gammopathy was identified in 1.0% (25/2400). Prevalence increased with age, 1.9% in patients aged &#x2265;&#x2009;65&#x2009;years and 0.7% (13/1755) aged &lt;&#x2009;65&#x2009;years. Patients with ALS and monoclonal gammopathy were older (63.2 vs. 57.1; p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.01) and predominantly male (7.3:1 vs. 1.5:1; p&#x2009;&lt;&#x2009;0.01). Immunotherapy targeting monoclonal gammopathy did not significantly affect disease progression (pre-treatment &#x394;FS 1.00&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;1.23 vs. post-treatment &#x394;FS 0.94&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;0.86; p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.46) or survival outcomes (median survival 55.0 vs. 57.0&#x2009;months; log-rank p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.93). Nerve conduction study did not correlate with clinical outcomes. IgM monoclonal gammopathy demonstrated later slower disease progression (initial &#x394;FS, overall &#x394;FS; p&#x2009;&lt;&#x2009;0.05) compared to IgA and IgG subtypes.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label=\"CONCLUSION\" NlmCategory=\"CONCLUSIONS\">Monoclonal gammopathy in Korean patients with ALS was not more prevalent than in the general population, and immunotherapy did not impact ALS progression or survival. Clinical features may vary by immunoglobulin subtype. This collectively suggests minimal clinical significance of monoclonal gammopathy in ALS.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2025 The Author(s). European Journal of Neurology published by John Wiley &amp; Sons Ltd on behalf of European Academy of Neurology.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN=\"Y\"><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Kim</LastName><ForeName>Hyunkee</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0000-0002-4022-1786</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neurology, Hanyang University College of Medicine, Seoul, Republic of Korea.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Cell Therapy Center, Hanyang University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Uhm</LastName><ForeName>Ji-Eun</ForeName><Initials>JE</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Hematology-Oncology, Department of Internal Medicine, Hanyang University C