io AM (2022) PD&#x2010;LI promotes rear retraction during persistent cell migration by altering integrin &#x3b2;4 dynamics. J Cell Biol 221, e202108083.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC8965106</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">35344032</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Manders EMM, Verbeek FJ &amp; Aten JA (1993) Measurement of co&#x2010;localization of objects in dual&#x2010;colour confocal images. J Microsc 169, 375&#x2013;382.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">33930978</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Dunn KW, Kamocka MM &amp; McDonald JH (2011) A practical guide to evaluating colocalization in biological microscopy. Am J Physiol Cell Physiol 300, 723&#x2013;742.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC3074624</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">21209361</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Van Steensel B, van Binnendijk E, Hornsby C, van der Voort H, Krozowski Z, de Kloet E &amp; van Driel R (1996) Partial colocalization of glucocorticoid and mineralocorticoid receptors in discrete compartments in nuclei of rat hippocampus neurons. J Cell Sci 109, 787&#x2013;792.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">8718670</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Lord SJ, Velle KB, Dyche Mullins R &amp; Fritz&#x2010;Laylin LK (2020) SuperPlots: communicating reproducibility and variability in cell biology. J Cell Biol 219, e202001064.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC7265319</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">32346721</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status=\"PubMed-not-MEDLINE\" Owner=\"NLM\"><PMID Version=\"1\">41394711</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>25</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>26</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel=\"Electronic\"><Journal><ISSN IssnType=\"Electronic\">2692-8205</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium=\"Internet\"><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Nov</Month><Day>30</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>bioRxiv : the preprint server for biology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>bioRxiv</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>U7 small nuclear RNA splice-switching therapeutics for STMN2 and UNC13A in Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis.</ArticleTitle><ELocationID EIdType=\"pii\" ValidYN=\"Y\">2025.11.26.690143</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType=\"doi\" ValidYN=\"Y\">10.1101/2025.11.26.690143</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>TDP-43 nuclear depletion in amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) causes de-repression of cryptic exons (CEs) in multiple transcripts, including <i>UNC13A</i> and <i>STMN2</i>, disrupting synaptic transmission and neurite outgrowth. We developed a therapeutic U7 snRNA (tU7) approach that suppresses TDP-43-dependent mis-splicing, restores target gene expression, rescues neuronal functions in human iPSC-derived neurons, and shows target engagement <i>in vivo</i>, positioning tU7-mediated splicing correction as a promising therapeutic strategy for ALS.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN=\"Y\"><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Mehta</LastName><ForeName>Puja R</ForeName><Initials>PR</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0000-0002-0255-407X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neuromuscular Diseases, UCL Queen Square Institute of Neurology, UCL Queen Square Motor Neuron Disease Centre, London, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>These authors contributed equally.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Solomon</LastName><ForeName>Tomas</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0000-0003-2600-6948</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>UK Dementia Research Institute, Institute of Psychiatry, Psychology &amp; Neuroscience, King's College London, London, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>These authors contributed equally.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Pickles</LastName><ForeName>Sarah</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0000-0001-7956-4586</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neuroscience, Mayo Clinic, Jacksonville, FL, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>These authors contributed equally.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Harley</LastName><ForeName>Peter</ForeName><Initials>P</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0000-0001-6689-0227</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neuromuscular Diseases, UCL Queen Square Institute of Neurology, UCL Queen Square Motor Neuron Disease Centre, London, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Barioglio</LastName><ForeName>Michela</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0009-0009-8360-2536</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neuromuscular Diseases, UCL Queen Square Institute of Neurology, UCL Queen Square Motor Neuron Disease Centre, London, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Schweingruber</LastName><ForeName>Christoph</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0000-0003-4505-9068</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>UK Dementia Research Institute, Institute of Psychiatry, Psychology &amp; Neuroscience, King's College London, London, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Marrero-Gagliardi</LastName><ForeName>Alessandro</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0000-0002-8470-4085</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neuromuscular Diseases, UCL Queen Square Institute of Neurology, UCL Queen Square Motor Neuron Disease Centre, London, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Au