tion</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI=\"Q000235\" MajorTopicYN=\"N\">genetics</QualifierName><QualifierName UI=\"Q000209\" MajorTopicYN=\"N\">etiology</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI=\"D003071\" MajorTopicYN=\"N\">Cognition</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI=\"Q000502\" MajorTopicYN=\"N\">physiology</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI=\"D000328\" MajorTopicYN=\"N\">Adult</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI=\"D009483\" MajorTopicYN=\"N\">Neuropsychological Tests</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI=\"D015331\" MajorTopicYN=\"N\">Cohort Studies</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI=\"D020022\" MajorTopicYN=\"N\">Genetic Predisposition to Disease</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI=\"D005858\" MajorTopicYN=\"N\" Type=\"Geographic\">Germany</DescriptorName></MeshHeading></MeshHeadingList><KeywordList Owner=\"NOTNLM\"><Keyword MajorTopicYN=\"N\">Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN=\"N\">UNC13A</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN=\"N\">cognition</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN=\"N\">rs12608932</Keyword></KeywordList></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus=\"medline\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>4</Month><Day>22</Day><Hour>0</Hour><Minute>36</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus=\"pubmed\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>1</Month><Day>2</Day><Hour>19</Hour><Minute>38</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus=\"entrez\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>1</Month><Day>2</Day><Hour>13</Hour><Minute>24</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>ppublish</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">41481541</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"doi\">10.1080/21678421.2025.2608238</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status=\"MEDLINE\" Owner=\"NLM\" IndexingMethod=\"Automated\"><PMID Version=\"1\">41485128</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>02</Month><Day>23</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>09</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel=\"Print-Electronic\"><Journal><ISSN IssnType=\"Electronic\">1554-8635</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium=\"Internet\"><Volume>22</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Mar</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Autophagy</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Autophagy</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>TBK1 orchestrates autophagy and endo-lysosomal pathways in human neurons.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>632</StartPage><EndPage>634</EndPage><MedlinePgn>632-634</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType=\"doi\" ValidYN=\"Y\">10.1080/15548627.2025.2609924</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Haploinsufficiency of TBK1 causes familial ALS and frontotemporal dementia (FTD), yet the mechanisms by which TBK1 loss leads to neurodegeneration remain unclear. Using deep proteomics and phospho-proteomics, we demonstrate that TBK1 regulates select macroautophagy/autophagy factors, targeting cargo receptors and autophagy initiation factors, and also sustains the phosphorylation of the late endosomal marker RAB7A in stem cells and stem cell-derived excitatory neurons. We further uncovered novel TBK1-dependent phosphorylation sites in the key autophagy protein SQSTM1/p62. Loss of TBK1 function results in a cell-autonomous neurodegenerative phenotype characterized by impaired neurite outgrowth and lysosomal dysfunction.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN=\"Y\"><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Mordes</LastName><ForeName>Daniel A</ForeName><Initials>DA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institute for Neurodegenerative Diseases, Weill Institute for Neurosciences and Department of Pathology, University of California, San Francisco, CA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Smeyers</LastName><ForeName>Julie</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationIn