0000000000691</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC4141994</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">25008398</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Crimella C, Cinzia Baschirotto, Arnoldi A, Tonelli A, Tenderini E, Airoldi G et al (2011) Mutations in the motor and stalk domains of KIF5A in spastic paraplegia type 10 and in axonal Charcot-Marie-Tooth type 2. Clin Genet 82(2):157&#x2013;164</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"doi\">10.1111/j.1399-0004.2011.01717.x</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">21623771</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Scaber J, Thompson AG, Farrimond L, Feneberg E, Proudfoot MJ, Ossher L et al (2023) Advantages of routine next-generation sequencing over standard genetic testing in the amyotrophic lateral sclerosis clinic. Eur J Neurol 30(8):2240</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"doi\">10.1111/ene.15855</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC10947345</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">37159497</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Zhang K, Liu Q, Shen D, Tai H, Liu S, Wang Z et al (2018) Mutation analysis of KIF5A in Chinese amyotrophic lateral sclerosis patients. Neurobiol Aging 73:229e1</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"doi\">10.1016/j.neurobiolaging.2018.08.006</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Tripolszki K, Gampawar P, Schmidt H, Nagy ZF, Nagy D, Kliv&#xe9;nyi P et al (2019) Comprehensive genetic analysis of a Hungarian amyotrophic lateral sclerosis cohort. Front Genet. ;10</Citation></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status=\"MEDLINE\" Owner=\"NLM\" IndexingMethod=\"Automated\"><PMID Version=\"1\">41766077</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>06</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>10</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel=\"Print-Electronic\"><Journal><ISSN IssnType=\"Electronic\">1537-1611</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium=\"Internet\"><Volume>27</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Mar</Month><Day>01</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of clinical neuromuscular disease</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Clin Neuromuscul Dis</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Respiratory Onset Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis in a Patient With C9orf72 Expansion.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>96</StartPage><EndPage>98</EndPage><MedlinePgn>96-98</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType=\"doi\" ValidYN=\"Y\">10.1097/CND.0000000000000556</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Respiratory-onset amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) is uncommon, accounting for less than 5% of all patients with ALS. Familial ALS is also uncommon, with the most common variant being related to a C9orf72 hexanucleotide repeat expansion. Respiratory-onset ALS in familial ALS is rare, with few cases discussed in the literature related to ERBB4, SOD1, and FUS variants. Here we present a case of respiratory-onset ALS related to a C9orf72 repeat expansion, expanding the spectrum of associated phenotypes associated with C9orf72 expansions and highlighting the importance of genetic testing in patients living with ALS.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 Wolters Kluwer Health, Inc. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN=\"Y\"><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Hass</LastName><ForeName>Reece M</ForeName><Initials>RM</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0000-0001-8298-3407</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neurology, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, MN.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Reiter-Campeau</LastName><ForeName>Sandra</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Laughlin</LastName><ForeName>Ruple S</ForeName><Initials>RS</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Liewluck</LastName><ForeName>Teerin</ForeName><Initials>T</Initi